         <abstract>
            <p>For splines of degree $k \geqslant 1$ with knots $-t_i = t_{2m + 1 - i} = 1 + q + q^2 + \cdots + q^{m - i}, i = 1,\ldots, m$, where $0 &lt; q &lt; 1$, it is shown that spline interpolation to continuous functions at nodes $\tau_i = \Sigma^k_1 w_jt_{i + j}, i = 1,\ldots, n = 2m - k - 1$, has operator norm $\|P\|$ which is bounded independently of $q$ and $m$ as $q$ tends to zero if and only if $(1 - w_1)^k &lt; \frac{1}{2}, (1 - w_k)^k &lt; \frac{1}{2}$, and $w_j &gt; 0, j = 1,\ldots, k$. The choice of nodes $\tau_i = \Sigma^{k + 1}_0 w_jt_{i + j}$ and the growth rate of $\|P\|$ with $k$ are also discussed.</p>
          </abstract>
